13, valetudinum. The plural is rare. lt means different kinds of ill-health, ‘infirmities.’ ‘Subsidia valetudinum’ means ‘contrivances to relieve our infirmities.’

14. Scilicet, ‘no doubt,’ ‘it is true,' expresses the granting of some- thing which, as far as it goes, is against the writer's or speaker's argument.

15. Bona mala, ‘good from evil.' The conjunctior] is omitted by a common Latin idiom between pairs of opposites.

35. Eiusque laudare fortunas. There are no words exactly to this effect in the words which Homer puts into the mouth of Polyphemus, but Cicero need mean no more than that the speech implies and suggests the contrast which he draws.

39. Surdaster, ‘ slightly deaf,' ‘hard os hearing.’ The termination ‘-aster ’ is more commonly used with names of trees or plants to signify the inferior or wild kinds of them, as ‘ oleaster‚' the wild olive. lt is apparently a kind of diminutive in either sense.

M. Crassus, the triumvir.
